13 SECTION 12. (1) The Statewide Preparedness Authority for Response Coordination is es-
14 tablished as an office within the Department of Public Safety Standards and Training. The
15 office is to be known as and may be cited as SPARC.
16 (2) The office is under the supervision and control of a facilitator, who is responsible for
17 the performance of the duties, functions and powers of the office.
18 (3) The Director of the Department of Public Safety Standards and Training shall appoint
19 the facilitator, who holds office at the pleasure of the director.
20 (4) The facilitator shall be paid a salary as provided by law or, if not so provided, as
21 prescribed by the director, with the approval of the Governor.
22 (5) For purposes of administration, the facilitator may organize and reorganize the office
23 as the facilitator considers necessary to properly conduct the work of the office.
24 (6) The facilitator may divide the functions of the office into administrative divisions. The
25 facilitator may appoint an individual to administer each division. The administrator of each
26 division serves at the pleasure of the facilitator and is not subject to the provisions of ORS
27 chapter 240. Each individual appointed under this subsection must be well qualified by tech-
28 nical training and experience in the functions to be performed by the individual.
29 (7) The office shall:
30 (a) Develop a standardized and expandable training environment for emergency response
31 training in consultation and collaboration with subject matter experts based on strategic,
32 operational and tactical assessments, evaluations and requirements; and
33 (b) Plan, develop, construct and operate facilities for emergency response training until
34 the facilitator determines that the facilities are fully operational, at which time control of
35 the facilities must be transferred to the Statewide Regional Training Office established under
36 section 18 of this 2026 Act.
37 SECTION 13. (1) SPARC shall develop and maintain a database to be known as the All-
38 Hazards Statewide Responder Database. The database is to be a centralized and comprehen-
39 sive repository of information regarding individuals and entities with skills or responsibilities
40 relevant to emergency management.
41 (2) The office shall negotiate any data sharing agreements with public and private entities
42 necessary to develop or maintain the database.
43 (3) The office shall collaborate, cooperate and coordinate with all appropriate private and
44 public entities with responsibility for the emergency support functions identified by the
45 Federal Emergency Management Agency to develop and maintain the database.
